reas secondary (indirect) healing (0.2-1mm contact zone) results in callus formation via nailing or cast-brace therapy.","line":12},{"title":"The size of the external callus on a healing fracture increases with the flexibility of the fixation, but this increased flexibility can make the area more unstable, potentially leading to a lack of bridging and, consequently, non-union.","target":"The size of the external callus on a healing fracture increases with the flexibility of the fixation, but this increased flexibility can make the area more unstable, potentially leading to a lack of bridging and, consequently, non-union.","line":12},{"title":"Tissue development in the fracture callus depends on its tolerance to local strain (which is uneven and changes during healing), with new tissues stiffening the fracture, reducing strain, and promoting bone formation.","target":"Tissue development in the fracture callus depends on its tolerance to local strain (which is uneven and changes during healing), with new tissues stiffening the fracture, reducing strain, and promoting bone formation.","line":12},{"title":"@Wildemann_2021_202406171535","target":"@Wildemann_2021_202406171535","line":19}],"key":"000 Zettelkasten/A callus is the healing tissue that connects the bone ends of a fracture..md"},
